Last year, the Department of Defense purchased 224 km of it.
The army has reserves for 225 years.
The problem is that the life of the ropes is from two to four years maximum.
The army bought detonating cords from the public company STV Group for 40 million kroner.
The General Staff gave as a reason for the achât of a huge amount of detonating cords to MF DNES that the soldiers use 60 km per year.
According to the calculations of reserve to be held made by the pyrotechnicians of the army, which MF DNES has contacted, it emerges that even the generals, the officers having a command, secretaries or the cleaning staff should have each year an exercise in explosives.
Alexander Vondra, Minister of Defence and Vlastimil Picek, commander of the army are no exception.
Only to argue the army's annual consumption of 60 km of detonating cords.
This distance corresponds to 25,000 explosions.
And even if that were true, the army's reserves could sustain it for 10 years.
If on the contrary it would be true that for the basic training of each of the new professionals it is enough to more than 2 m of detonating cords, as the experts say, it means that the army with its new purchase has ensured - with also the consumption of special units and engineering - reserves for the 225 years mentioned.
However, soldiers from the Rapid Intervention Brigade have recently complained to Minister Vondra that they have almost no ammunition for their handguns and that shooting sessions are limited due to the need for money.
About the lack of body linen we don't talk about it.
"And I don't mind if they buy such a large amount of detonating cords from us."
“And that’s their decision and they really know what they’re doing.”
“For us the military is a good customer that we strive as traders to please,” says STV Group sales manager Jan Decky.
Jan Pejsek, a spokesman for the Ministry of Defence, argues that hundreds of miles of explosive cords will be hit by the fact that the army will have these "munitions" in reserve for 10 years.
Jan Decky of STV Group, however, reports only four years of life of the detonating cords and the pyrotechnicians of the police and army of only two years.
“If they are perfectly stored in the depots, it can even go up to four years,” said one who does not want his name published given the criticism of the army.
The life span passed, each munition must be tested to see if it remains intact and does not threaten the life of the soldier.
