Today the Ministry of Defence has big problems for the neutralization of tens of tons of ammunition from the time of the Warsaw Pact when the Czechoslovak army of two hundred thousand men was preparing to move, heading on the Rhine.
What awaits in a few years this Czech army that MF DNES has contacted: neutralize hundreds of kilometers of old detonating cords that it buys today "cheap".
So far, I have benefited from the contacts I have gained through the contests.
The franchised sale of his hotel helped Lukas Pytloun to win the Best Individual Entrepreneur competition.
The winner of last year’s Best Individual Entrepreneur contest was 28-year-old entrepreneur Lukas Pytloun.
His adventure to success is like in a movie.
Lukas Pytloun loved to travel.
And abroad, he realized that in Libérec there was a lack of a quality accommodation site at a reasonable price.
From his savings on what he had earned when he worked abroad and with the help of a bank loan he bought a small building of 5 apartments half demolished.
Knowing that he was still a student in the third year of higher education, it was a courageous action.
"The relationship between the quality and the price of accommodation in our region made me want to do something," says Lucas Pytloun.
He began to rent the first apartment rebuilt to foreign workers.
He reinvested the profit in the building which he transformed into a pension with 54 beds.
Since then, his entrepreneurial action has allowed him to open in Libérec 4 pensions, two style restaurants and two hotels with a total capacity of nearly 300 beds of all categories of accommodation.
The most comfortable of them was until recently the four-star Pytloun design hotel.
This year, another of the same quality came to him.
“We just signed a contract with a hotel in Ostrova U Tise where we sold our franchise concept and other candidates for the Pytloun hotel franchise came forward,” the No. 1 contractor said.
"And for the sale of the license for the operation of a large-scale hotel the victory in the entrepreneur of the year contest served well," adds Pytloun with gratitude.
The victory brought him more popularity and to be known in Liberec and its surroundings.
“People recognized me in the streets, congratulated me often and, I must say, it was very pleasant,” he recalls.
He recommends participation in this contest to all those who strive to do something.
It is not necessary to win but any opportunity to be visible is good.
He says that he uses his contacts and knowledge until today that he could not have obtained in any other way.
"With those I met through the contest I started to maintain business relationships regularly.
According to him, the reputation linked to success also had an impact on employees.
And he's about 70.
"I see in them above all the loyalty and pride of having committed to something that has generally been recognized."
"This is not, by far, the only result of my personal work, but the result of a good work of all of us together.
“Only my name is pushed forward,” says Lucas Pytloun modestly.
I wish my successor a better year than the one we had at Farmet.
The euphoria of victory has been quickly replaced by the effects of the crisis.
Thanks to the winner’s sense of purpose Farmet has the worst moments behind him.
The one who picked up the prize in Slovansky dum for the first place in the contest for the Firm of the Year organized by Vodaphone last year is Karel Zdarsky the owner of the company Farmet.
The jury rewarded the efforts with which it transformed a tool shop in Ceska Skalice into a firm with a turnover of 100 million crowns.
“I can say that the award not only encouraged me my collaborators and increased our self-confidence to fight against the competition,” said the winner of last year’s competition.
At the beginning of the history of the company Farmet there was the desire to do something useful.
And so when the state offered Karel Zdrasky’s father to rent the small workshop as compensation after the confiscation of property by the communists, he did not hesitate for long, refused a career at a firm where he worked at the time, and created a company with a few comrades in his father’s entourage for the manufacture of plastic bathtubs.
Not very long after they began to specialize in vegetable oil presses.
After eighteen years, it has become the largest manufacturer of automatic presses in Central Europe.
The company was known even in the non-specialized public after the success obtained in the contest through the media.
“Not only did our customers start to really get to know the Farmet brand better but also the foreign partners who started to realize that they were collaborating with a company that got the most success in its home country,” says Karel Zdarsky.
But the past year has not happened at Farmet only in the euphoria of victory.
The company's assessment was based on economic results from 2008 and in part from 2009.
And precisely in 2009 it was the most difficult year for the sale of engineering machinery.
At the height of the crisis, which did not really affect the citizens, companies were forced to stop their investment projects and begin to limit their purchases of new materials and technologies.
“We obviously did not escape this situation.”
“The turnover fell by 40 percent, and we had to limit our production and even lay off,” Zdarsky said.
A viable society must know that from time to time unpopular measures must be taken.
But they managed the situation properly and maintained beneficial results even though they were lower than they had before the crisis.
However, at Farmet, they continued without compromise to invest in research and development.
“We built with the endowments a training and research center, strengthened the presentation of the company in international trade fairs and won the main awards in national exhibitions,” says Zdarsky.
Everything suggests that the crisis is behind them.
The numbers go up and with them the number of employees as well.
“To the new winner I wish this pleasant feeling of victory but in a calm atmosphere,” says Karel Zdarsky.
The investigation that removes insane regulations.
The survey on the Absurdity of the Year is for the fourth time a part of the business clan.
Some absurd regulations could be removed.
The inglorious winner of this year's survey on the Absurdity of the Year was the obligation to bring to the offices documents that officials can obtain online.
More than a third of the 4,000 voters voted for it.
For example, the administration of social affairs requested a paper extract from the commercial register while the official can obtain it in two mouse clicks.
It changes because of the investigation.
“The Czech Social Insurance Administration will no longer ask for an extract from the Commercial Register for insurance payment checks,” said Jana Buranova, spokesman for the Czech Social Insurance Administration (CSSZ).
Bringing out all the regulations and decrees that companies and entrepreneurs must fulfill in the Czech Republic and having those that are absurd removed is the meaning of this year's absurdity contest.
This survey is again this year for the fourth time a part of the business clan organized by Hospodarske noviny and has even greater popularity.
If last year 3000 voters came forward, it is at least 4000 this year that have brought their vote.
And it is not surprising, there are in our country the most various legal obligations that only slow down the company, and, this, more and more.
“We may be the number of documents to fill out for tax returns to the top places in the world,” says Karel Havlicek of the Association of Small and Medium Enterprises and Entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic.
Simplification of entrepreneurial activity has become a proclaimed goal of all governments in recent years.
Compared to the whole world, the situation in the Czech Republic is not improving at all.
According to the World Bank, the Czech Republic ranks 74th in terms of business conditions, 8 places higher than last year.
The Absurdity of the Year competition was first established in 2006 and continues each year under the same scenario.
Anyone can report administrative and bureaucratic nonsense every year from April to the end of September, the last deadline before the end of the competition.
To report there is the website www.firmaroku.cz. Then the contest organizer chooses seven candidates for "anti-prize" and leaves the public to vote during the month of October on the website www.firmaroku.cz/absurdita and on www.ihned.cz.
The absurdity that received the highest number of votes is declared the winner.
Until the last survey last year, there were a hundred, or more precisely 105 regulations and decrees that lost their meaning of existence.
Comments are sent by entrepreneurs but also professional unions and teachers.
Among the "finalists" of the contest, therefore among the nominees is for example the obligation that maintenance vehicles of highways and expressways pay the tolls, or that contractors with twenty employees, repaint two offices and two toilets every two years.
The list of the seven proposals is published on the competition website.
The proclamation of the contest, which always begins in early November at Wenceslas Square in Prague, is part of a happening that regularly involves personalities from political and public life.
This year, for example, Eva Svobodova, director of the Association for Small and Medium Enterprises of the Czech Republic, or Petr Kuzel, president of the Chamber of Commerce of the Czech Republic, attended the high point of the competition.
“Economic prosperity cannot work when the state puts stumbling blocks in the legs of entrepreneurs and for that my goal is to delete, every year, at least three dozen paragraphs that today only complicate the business,” said Martin Kocourek, the Minister of Industry and Trade.
The effort to suppress absurd decrees is not a sword in the water.
In 2007, what did not please people was the obligation of the entrepreneurs to declare three days before to the office for the sole proprietorship in the place where the company is located, the intention to go to an exhibition or a pilgrimage with a stand.
This obligation was removed with the amendment of the Individual Business Act.
The second most popular requirement in 2007, which was to report a 30-day foreign employee to the Labour Office, was removed with the text of the so-called Green Card Act.
And everything is ok until the third session of the contest.
The absurdity of the year 2009 was the decree for physiotherapists to have a large mirror in their office, a refrigerator and two automatic scales.
This was changed by order of the Ministry of Health last year – the requirement to have a refrigerator was removed.
A new category rewards socially responsible firms.
Ecological, humanitarian, training or sports projects are evaluated.
The novelty of this year's competition of Hospodarske Noviny, which already exists for 5 years, is the category called the Responsible Firm of the year 2010.
The premise of this contest is reasonable and fair business support.
“We want to support companies that monitor the impact of their company on the environment and conduct a socially responsible activity,” says Patrick Bartholdy, the regional manager of the mobile operator, Vodaphone, which is the guarantor and promoter of this contest, as in the case of the contest for the rebel of the year.
For this first year of this subcategory of the competition of the firm of the year 2010, organized by the firm Vodaphone, have registered the companies that do not succeed with a single long-term goal for the company.
The adventure of each of them is rich of inspirations and an independent article would be to edit.
Although the purpose of their business is different from each other, their support and forecasting activity can be seen as the denominator of their efforts.
In one case, it concerns people with disabilities and the personal or health problems of their employees.
Among the fourteen finalists for the entire Czech Republic is the software company Et Netera which supports the creation of informal sports teams of their employees who then participate in many tournaments in different sports disciplines.
Another example of a firm responsible for the Pardubice region is the company Isolit-Bravo which has been the main contributor to the endowment fund that sponsors children with disabilities for 17 years.
The old paper factory in Podebrad, which employs more than 70 per cent of employees with health problems, was awarded the title of Responsible for the Central Bohemian Region and placed third in the region in Vodaphone's Firm of the Year competition.
In Olomouc, it is MiRyz Soft, a financial company, which has earned for having introduced flexible working hours and even decreased up to 35 hours per week on average and, without, proportionately, lower wages.
The jury also awarded her the title because she primarily buys from Czech manufacturers, supports a local activity and cares about the environment.
“We strive to recycle as much as possible so that our business and administration have the least impact on the environment,” said Miluse Ryznarova, the company’s executive director.
the company responsible for IT Enlogit of the Region of Usti also thinks about the health of its employees and has set them for each laptop an ergonomic chair and keyboard, encourages their work from home and uses the catering services of a local protected factory for its actions.
“We also support the Man in the Shadow Foundation, which helps the local Roma community,” said Ondrej Suchy, the company’s representative.
At the very last rank is, also for its activities, a company of Washing and cleaning of the region of Karlovy Vary, which participates in the retirement insurance of its employees in the form of bonuses above the standards.
"In our society we contribute to food, transportation, increased skills and leisure," says Joseph Strapac of the construction company Bruntal Czasch, winner for the Moravian-Silesian region.
All the regional finalists for Vodaphone’s Firm of the Year competition were automatically registered in the Responsible Company category, who had completed the questionnaires attached to the registration document and sent it back to the organiser before August 15.
Improper or incomplete answers in the questionnaire were removed from the contest by the organizer.
"If the representatives of the competing firms had not answered the questions, they could not participate in the competition of the Responsible firm but were not disqualified from the "principal" competition the Vodaphone Firm of the Year".
"Independent registration is not possible because it is a subcategory of the main competition of the Firm of the Year," explains Karel Goldman of the organizing agency Bison&Rose.
At the Land Fund in Plzen, police made arrests during a public contest
In the Land Fund building in Plzen, anti-corruption police have made arrests in recent days.
Detectives handcuffed the local entrepreneur and real estate trader Lubos. G.
The latter had tried to manipulate a public tender for the settlement of a request for restitution in such a way that the proposed land was obtained by a specific candidate.
He had to pay Lubos G. half a million crowns.
“At the moment I can only confirm that the police are prosecuting a person for insider trading in connection with a public tender and competition,” Plzen prosecutor Antonie Zelena told the Pravo newspaper, knowing that it is forbidden to provide more explanations because the investigation is ongoing.
Police released the 46-year-old entrepreneur after 24 hours.
To know how it could influence a public competition, one can only speculate in view of the so little official information.
On a question from Pravo, Lubomira Cerna Land Fund spokeswoman said that the police had actually made an arrest in Plzen at a separate workplace during the public competition.
"It was a client and not an employee," she said.
The public competition according to Cerna has the real name "Call to propose rights for the transfer of land according to the Law on the Land" and is set up when several candidates beneficiaries of rights appear.
“These people are proposing, as part of the appeal, a higher value of their rights to reside, which must be settled before the value of the land is announced.”
"According to the proposed rights, a classification of the purchasers is set up and the Land Fund then transfers the land to the person who has proposed the highest rights," explained the spokesman of the Fund.
Lubos G. had, it is clear, the information concerning the persons who had registered for the appeal and since he himself was also a beneficiary because he had bought a large number of rights to restitution, he had proposed to the candidates in the field not to participate in the competition.
And he was probably cashing in by the fact of withdrawing.
This would explain why he had so much money in his possession at the time of his arrest.
Lubos G. had contacts well above the standards at the FdT (Fonds des Terrains).
He was included in the case of the former head of the FfT Vaclav Sankot who was prosecuted for editing land for which the decision to set up a construction had already been edited.
Precisely Lubos G. had obtained, for example, land for the construction of public communications, specifically in the place where the access road to the industrial zone of Borske Pole was to be built.
Later he exchanged it with the town hall for a building in the historic center of the city whose value is far superior.
The town hall was obliged to accept because otherwise it risked jeopardizing the construction by blocking the land.
Households will pay an additional 100 crowns per month for housing.
Households will have to pay a supplement not only for all types of energy but also for water and sanitation, heating supplies and in some places rents will also increase.
As of January, families will have to draw up to a hundred crowns from their wallets monthly more than now.
Electricity increases by 4.6 percent, gas almost 2 percent more expensive, in some localities you will have to pay up to a tenth more for water supply and in many places central heating supplies will also be more expensive.
The increase in electricity is expected to be around 100 kroner annually for apartment households than at present.
However, all suppliers have reduced electricity prices in view of the significant development in encouraging the manufacture of renewable energies, in particular photovoltaic batteries.
Gas increases moderately but of course at the time when people need it most to heat and therefore have the greatest consumption.
We can also count a hundred more crowns.
Although electricity and gas are increasing throughout the Czech Republic, the change in the price of central heating differs from city to city.
These are mainly the largest municipalities that plan the price increase.
For example, households in Pardubice or Hradec Kraloce will pay almost 50 crowns more per month for central heating starting in January, families in Libérec will pay more than 1,000 crowns annually.
For the inhabitants of Prague is preparing an increase of 9 percent for water and sanitation in case the city increases the infrastructure rents.
If the rents do not change the pragois will pay an extra 6.8 percent.
The price in Prague will still be among the lowest compared to the entire country.
In North Bohemia, where prices are already among the highest, water and sanitation are up 7.4 percent.
Rent prices will increase significantly, for example, in the 450 thousand apartments rented from January, i.e. at the end of the regulation.
For example the company CPI Byty which owns in Usti nad Labem almost 2500 apartments, has decided an increase of up to 100 percent.
Those who do not agree with the new rent increase will be brought before the courts by the company.
Regulated rents that people pay in nearly 300,000 apartments could increase next year by 10 percent.
Czech children get drunk with rum and fernet. The beer is out of fashion and acts very slowly.
Fernet, rum, vodka and exceptionally also the best brand of whisky are stolen from the parents.
These are drinks that most often bring those who are drunk, who are not yet fifteen years old, into the hands of the doctor.
Children who are treated in the hospital for recidivism are no exception.
This results from the experience of doctors who encounter cases similar to admissions from the children's departments of hospitals.
“Beers or wines are no longer in fashion because it takes time to be drunk.”
“The trend is really towards strong alcohol,” said Pravo Ludek Pelikan, head of the children’s department at Horovice hospital in central Bohemia.
"When they manage to grab a daddy's bottle in the cupboard, it's sometimes wisky but it's the fernet and vodka that prevail."
“Vodka has this advantage that they can mix it with fruit juice and thus not smell it,” explains the Head of the department.
Eva Jurinova, spokesman for Motol Hospital, also agrees.
“In general, it’s rum or fernet.”
“Today it’s alcohol in fashion, especially in elementary schools.”
“In some cases, it was slivovice that they brought home,” Jurinova added.
According to the head of department Pelikan, seeing drunken children between the ages of thirteen and fourteen at hospital admissions is a normal phenomenon.
Before working in Horovice since last year, he was in Motol where he practiced ten years precisely in pediatrics where ambulances brought schoolchildren from large areas completely drunk.
"A young girl was hospitalized like this four times.
“She started her career at the age of twelve when she was brought in with 3.5 per thousand alcohol in her blood plus a mix with ecstasy,” the doctor said.
"She was at the Holesovice Exhibition Park at a party."
"What's interesting is that it didn't seem strange to the mother that her daughter was absent for 48 hours," he said.
It is precisely the parents' unselfishness or their unusual tolerance for the fact that their offspring indulge in drinking that is the main cause of the development of alcoholism in children.
According to specialists, however, we are not talking about dependence, in its strict sense, for children.
"Under the term alcoholic we hear a chronic dependence on alcohol for several years with all the phenomena that follow from it but that we do not find in children."
“In those who repeatedly use alcohol, it is more of a socio-familial background that is significantly unfavorable,” explained the Head of Department Pelikan.
According to spokeswoman Jurinova, about forty drunk children were hospitalized this year until mid-November in the pediatric clinic in Motol.
Only cases with a grâve intoxication requiring hospitalization are integrated into the statistics.
Drunk children who are after emergency care brought home by parents or police are not counted.
In addition to the cases of children who sit down and drink a bottle of alcohol after school, according to Pelikan there are three seasonal waves with which one can count: the day of the witches, the Saint Sylvester and the end of the school year.
"Either they drink in spite of bad results or on the contrary they celebrate the beginning of the holidays."
“Of course I experienced on Witches’ Day an admission of 7 drunk children at once,” Pelikan said.
The drunken child who spent the night in the hospital in rehab under medical supervision is paradoxically in a better position than the one who returned home and suffers the day after the "wooden hangover".
Morning headaches caused by dehydration and lack of glucose are eliminated by an infusion of glucose and nutrients that the body needs.
"They are better off because they have a great evening and then a sweet awakening and nothing hurts them."
“They are only amazed at where they are,” adds Pelikan knowing that from time to time it spoils the good mood of patients at least with the note to pay for their care.
Ambulance transport and intensive care bed hospitalization can go up to tens of thousands of kroner.
“From time to time, I have applied this as a means of education by counting on these children how much their drunkenness has cost and that they could spend the entire summer in seasonal work to pay off a single evening,” Pelikan added.
However, according to him, the health insurance companies in their declining management, which should recover from the parents the expenses related to the care, do not deal with the cases of drunk children.
Two L-159 aircraft are in foreign hands in Spain for the first time.
Two of the five L-159 aircraft, against which the Ministry of Defense exchanged Casa C-295M transport aircraft, took off on Tuesday for Seville in Spain where the manufacturer of Casa-EADS aircraft is headquartered.
This is the first time aircraft of this type have become the property of anyone other than the Czech Army.
However, they have been abroad as part of exercises or demonstration flights.
These are the two-seater versions of the L-159T1 that were up to now in service in the Czech army and were in flight condition.
The remaining three devices are single-seat versions of the L-159.
They are currently stationed at Aéro Vodochody and the commercial intermediary - Omnipol - took them into account last week.
According to Jan Pejsek of the Ministry of Defence's press department, the physical departure of Vodochody's planes is still unknown.
"Single-seat L-159 aircraft planned for the exchange were taken from long-stocked aircraft without this causing any additional charges or investments for the Ministry of Defence."
“The L-159 T1 two-seaters were traded in the state,” said Pravo Pejsek.
He added that the army will not remain without two-seater since the ministry signed in May 2009 with Aéro Vodochody an agreement worth 200 million crowns for the transformation of four unused L-159 single-seaters into two two-seaters.
The army took delivery of the first aircraft in July, with the second scheduled for delivery at the end of this year.
According to Pejsek EADS is committed to introducing aircraft into the equipment of some Alliance countries.
“The contract clearly states that the one who takes L-159 aircraft into account is EADS and that they will be used to train pilots from NATO member countries.”
“It’s therefore up to the one who takes into account how to achieve this,” Pejsek said.
Hospodarske noviny announced some time ago that the Spanish army is not interested in the L-159.
The exchange of five L-159s for a Casa aircraft and the purchase of three more aircraft for 3.5 billion crowns was endorsed last year by the government of Mirek Topomanek.
The Ministry of Defence did not call for tenders and contacted EADS directly.
The defence management argued that the exchange would ensure the future export of the L-159 to foreign countries.
The Czech army bought 72 aircraft from Aéro Vodochody and only used 24 of them, wanting to sell the rest.
The purchase of Casa aircraft will likely have legal implications.
However, the European Commission has filed a complaint against the Czech Ministry of Defence with the European Court of Justice because the planes should have been chosen as part of a European-wide call for tenders and in no case by contacting a manufacturer directly.
The army has already taken delivery of three Casa planes, the last one is expected to arrive at Prague Kbely airport in two weeks.
Longer index than ring finger is a sign of low cancer risk
Men who have an index finger longer than the ring finger are at a lower risk of getting prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British magazine Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our findings show that the relative length of the finger serves as a simple test for prostate cancer risk, especially for men before age 60,” said study co-author Ros Eeles, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should be tested for prostate cancer, including combining it with genetic risk or other aggravating factors like family health history, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009 she followed with her colleagues in Great Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the right hand index finger shorter than the ring finger.
For them, as for the 19 percent of those who had the same length of fingers, the same probability of prostate cancer was found.
In the case of those who had the index longer than the ring finger the risk fell to 33 percent, however, for men before age 60 the decrease in risk reached 87 percent.
The ratio of the length of the two fingers mentioned - formed during the prenatal period - indicates in particular different levels of sex hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer index.
Previous research had shown that it is precisely testosterone that helps the development of prostate cancer.
Professor Vacla Paces, a renowned Czech geneticist and former president of the Academy of Sciences, told CTK that he is aware of this study but does not seem to him, it seems, that the relationship between finger length and cancer is "completely demonstrated".
