In the weeks after suddenly becoming a widow, Argentina’s President Cristina Fernandez benefited from a wave of public sympathy that improved her approval rate by 20 points, to more than 50%; this is her highest level since she was elected in 2007.
Still, turning this into a successful campaign for a second term in an election next year could depend on Ms. Fernandez’s choice, visibly in mourning, whether or not she abandons the intransigence of her late husband, predecessor and former political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, in this regard, the signs remain confused.
Kirchner, who continued to manage economic policy even after his wife succeeded him as president, used to develop budgets that underestimated tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
