The lion is ready to blush again, the restructuring of MGM is waiting for the final green light of the court
After 18 months of turbulence and uncertainty, MGM finally got the green light to start from scratch.
A federal bankruptcy judge in New York on Thursday officially praised the creditors’ “pre-packaged” plan that roughly $5 billion of debt would be wiped out; paving the way for the entertainment company, which is 86 years old, to focus its efforts on producing and distributing movies and TV shows.
With Thursday’s decision that the plan meets the requirements of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code, no legal hurdles remain before MGM to refloat under the tutelage of Entertainment Spyglass founders Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the general managers of what will be a lean studio.
The staff will be reduced to about 320 out of 400 at the start.
MGM will not actually emerge from Chapter 11 until JPMorgan Chase enters into a $500 million credit facility to finance MGM's new operations and productions.
