Bringing a softer side to policing in China
Tang Shenbin walked a city square as an urban sergeant in training by sternly inspecting his nerve charges, issuing orders in a low voice with a military authority.
He wanted the female members of chengguan – imposing public order officials in China, feared and despised for their arbitrary repression and penchant for violence – to convey a certain impression to a group of spectators.
"Stand up straight!"
"Be sharp!"
Show them, he says, "what pretty girls look like!"
Four girls who had barely spent their teenage years in white gloves, dressed in identical olive-coloured jackets and trousers, were standing by.
Four pairs of black heeled shoes, aligned to the ruler.
Four neat hats perfectly perched on top of hair tied by a striped knot in blue and white.
“Personally, I think they look average,” Tang said, disdainfully.
"The models are pretty."
More than one government has tried to refresh the image of China’s urban inspectors.
One city required all new recruits to have a higher degree.
Guangdong province traded the gray-green uniforms for a supposedly more engaging blue.
Wuhan, Central China, replaced the blindfolds with the loud way: In 2009, a report reported that 50 officers had surrounded an uncontrollable snack cart by casting black glances, firmly for half an hour, until the peddler repackaged his belongings and left.
Xindu, an urban district of 680,000 people in Chengdu, has chosen to do a large image operation.
Since 2003, the district has supplemented its urban street police with 13 women, specially chosen for their appearance, their curves and their young age.
The idea is to give the police a softer, more feminine side.
Unfortunately, even Scarlett Johansson might have trouble catching eye on China’s underground urban brigade
And for good reason, the critics will say.
Unlike the police, these officers are only allowed to enforce municipal orders by imposing fines or other administrative penalties.
But the Chinese media portrays the news from a different reality.
In January 2008, inspectors in Hubei province beat an observer to death after he used his mobile phone to film them dispersing a protest against a garbage dump.
Last year, a training manual for Beijing inspectors, stolen and posted online, describes how to effectively defeat offenders without emitting blood.
This year in Shanghai, a watermelon hawker was abandoned with a brain injury after a fight with five officers.
A violent video game, available via online download, shows Chinese inspectors trained to assault street vendors.
“Chengguan has marked the government,” China Daily, a national publication, lamented last year after yet another controversy over tactics.
The newspaper called for a "true complete cleanup."
Skeptics say the approach is a long way off.
After the district made an announcement in October to find eight new female recruits, an editorial in The Beijing Evening News questioned whether women had real jobs or were just tourist entertainment.
The answer seems to be a bit of both.
The district’s announcement required female candidates, aged between 18 to 22, to have a beautiful figure and “the five facial features in the right order.”
They must be larger than average in size, 1.6 meters or 5 feet, 2 1/2 inches.
Retirement at age 26 is mandatory.
Officers said the work was physically too painful for women over 25.
“It’s their image that’s important,” a district officer told Rednet.com, a quasi-government website.
"First, the external qualities of the candidates will determine whether they are suitable; these are the height, weight, facial features, etc."
Then comes the temperament and the "inner qualities."
The women of Chengguan are like flower vases, he said, adding: "In addition to being vases, they will have other responsibilities.
Zheng Lihua, deputy director of the city's district management office, does not agree with this description.
But he noted that height requirements were the standard in many Chinese job postings for both sexes.
This is the case of the requirement relating to the order of facial features.
That this means beautiful is a topic of debate among the Chinese.
Certainly, disabled or disfigured people should not apply.
“We can’t let a limp person or a hunchback come and serve here,” Zheng said.
"He wouldn't give a good picture."
Liu Yi, who patrols Baoguang Square near a monastery, is 22 years old and has appleted cheeks with a finely curved mouth.
She doesn’t consider highlighting her appearance as sexist, she said.
“Do you think I look sexy in that uniform?” she asked disillusionedly.
Xu Yang, his 21-year-old dimpled colleague, says, “Our job is to present the image of the city.”
They do not object to their mandate being limited, they said, because they have greater career ambitions than simply chasing sellers into the back alleys where they are supposed to limit their activities.
Each morning, the team confronts a dozen street vendors who quickly move on foot or by bike, trying to sell as many buns or bowls of tofu as possible before fleeing.
"Master Wang, you must go."
“We’ve told you many times before!” said Ms. Xu as a salesman fled on foot, temporarily abandoning his noodle-cart.
Agents describe their duties as monotonous rather than fiery.
“It’s pretty much the same every day,” said Huang Jing, 20, who studies after-work marketing.
"Great routine."
One reason is that female agents do not have the power of their male counterparts to confiscate the goods of the sellers.
They can only threaten to report offenders to their male superiors.
This tends to protect them from sudden public exposures of animosity against bureaucracy that are common throughout China.
This year, hundreds of citizens in Kunming, the capital of Yunnan province, revolted after false rumors spread that chengguan agents had killed a salesman.
In one night, more than a dozen chengguan police and officers were injured, 14 government vehicles were overturned or set on fire.
Xindu has so far escaped such violence.
But calm is hardly guaranteed.
Just two blocks from placid Baoguang Square, where female officers were patrolling that morning, more than 50 people gathered around the corner.
Officers confiscated a motorcycle that was being repaired on the sidewalk rather than in a store, as required by regulation.
The owner of the motorcycle was screaming scandalously.
A 15-minute standoff followed before the grim-faced policemen nudged their way to their vehicle and drove off at full speed with the motorcycle and its owner.
Li Xuedong, 40, a coordinator attached to the men’s team, stayed behind, his white badge returned to hide his name.
Like female officers, coordinators - men aged 40 or older - play a purely supportive role.
Unlike them, they are not trained to maintain a waxed image.
“Sometimes we fight verbally.”
“Sometimes we fight physically,” Li said in a neutral tone.
“Most of the time, it’s the audience that starts.”
Prosecutors will not charge Senator Ensign
Attorneys for the Justice Department have lifted criminal charges against Senator John Ensign, stemming from a case related to an aide from a former campaign and his efforts to get lobbying work for the woman's husband, the senator's lawyers said Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Nevada Republican who was considered a possible Republican presidential candidate in 2012 until the scandal surrounding his case made national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Ensign’s office said he was “very happy” with the decision, the result of a year-long investigation.
The honourable senator could still be exposed to disciplinary action by the Senate ethics committee.
Ensign’s lawyers said the Justice Department had “informed that Senator Ensign is no longer under investigation and that he has no intention of maintaining any charges against him in this matter.”
The Department of Justice has refrained from commenting on this.
The announcement came as a kind of surprise to many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, who said there was significant evidence that Ensign had conspired to violate a federal criminal lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails and other documents, first released in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, get lucrative lobbying work to win the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, about the senator's case with her.
Mrs. Hampton once served as treasurer in an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; in accordance with the documents and interviews.
Since Mr. Hampton had recently been a collaborator with Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited by law from lobbying his former employer or the Senate as a whole for one year.
Ethics experts have argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, appears to be at odds with the so-called lobby revolving door ban.
From the evidence that has been made public, “there appears to be prima facie evidence of a plot to violate and materially violate revolving door law,” said Stanley Brand, a Washington attorney who specializes in defending clients from a government investigation.
While the department's judge declined to explain the reasoning that led to the Ensign decision, Brand and other ethics lawyers said the department appeared to be wary of political prosecution after a number of high-profile setbacks by its public integrity section, including last year's decision to drop charges against former Senator Ted Stevens accused of misconduct.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the citizens' executive director for accountability and ethics in Washington, a advocacy group that received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basicly says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them", she added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign’s senior lawyer, said in an interview that he received a phone call on Monday from a Justice Department prosecutor and a follow-up the next day, telling him that the department was not seeking charges against his client.
Ensign’s team of lawyers had cooperated with prosecutors to try to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed Wednesday in a statement, “had acted in accordance with the law.”
Mr. Coggins refused to specify the legal arguments he had made to the prosecution.
“I’m not comfortable getting into the details of my discussions with the Justice Department, except to say that we think they made the right decision,” he said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission decided to drop an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that the $96,000 payment by Ensign’s parents to the Hamptons violated federal election law.
The election commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a major Nevada company that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company welcomed Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Mr. Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told him that he was "marriage" the Department of the Interior on an issue in dispute.
Mr. Ensign also attended a luncheon with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and asked the Secretary of Transportation to schedule a meeting on behalf of the airline after he engaged Mr. Hampton to lobby.
When news of the case surfaced last year, Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned as the fourth-ranking Republican in the Senate.
After maintaining a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign said two weeks ago that he intends to seek a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokesman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped that the ethics committee would quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and end its investigation.
Senator Ensign looks forward to continuing his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she says.
Cheshire's appeal will point to Twitter
Half a dozen of them were typing away in the rows of the courtroom.
Every minute they sent reports of horrific testimonies via Twitter.
In the end, the defense said there were more than 140,000 messages about the trial of the rape case and the children tied to their bed in a house that was set on fire.
On Thursday, the widely followed trial of Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three members of the Cheshire family in Connecticut, is expected to lead to an official end where the judge would impose the death penalty, voted by the jury.
But Hayes’s lawyers have already filed evidence in court that outlines arguments of appeal, likely to occupy the courts for years.
What is provocative is that the intense reporting on the trial – as well as the widespread and widespread use by Twitter journalists – created a “circus atmosphere,” a saturation so widespread and instantaneous with incendiary details that the jury was misinfluenced by the public’s passions.
The application could push appellate judges to debate whether new technologies require new rules in courtrooms.
“I have experienced this in this trial; I think there is a real danger that the introduction of new technologies in the courtrooms is undermining the human rights to a fair trial,” said Thomas J. Ullmann, a lawyer for Mr. Hayes, chief lawyer.
Trial judge Jon C. Bleue of the State Superior Court laconically rejected the claims in last week’s judgment, saying the media was “carefully controlled” and there was no evidence that the jury was driven by passion.
But that doesn’t seem to be the last word on the issue.
Courts of appeal have recognized for decades that media coverage of notorious cases can raise questions about the fairness of a trial.
In a landmark 1966 ruling, the U.S. Supreme Court overturned the conviction of Cleveland osteopath Dr. Sam Sheppard for the murder of his wife, arguing in its ruling that there was a "carnival atmosphere at trial" because of the media.
The crime is considered by some to have been the inspiration for the TV show and film "The Fugitive".
Some lawyers have said that the appeals courts seized to review Hayes’ conviction half a century later may be curious given the argument that new rules may be needed to manage the courtroom communications, unimaginable at the time of Dr. Sheppard’s case.
“There is a general reason to worry about the impact of new media” in large-scale trials, said John J. Donohue III, a professor at Stanford Law School who studied the death penalty in Connecticut and wrote a report that it was arbitrarily enforced.
Professor Donohue says some appellate judges may be intrigued by the idea that limiting instant communication from courtrooms could allow for fairer trials.
Twitter’s case is just one of many described by Hayes’ lawyers, likely to be discussed for years, delaying execution.
Defense lawyers also claim, for example, that Hayes was allegedly harmed when Judge Blue refused to allow them to test the reactions of potential jurors by showing them gruesome photos of criminal scenes during jury selection.
Some of the jurors said they were horrified by the photos of the victims, Jennifer Hawke-Petit, 48, and her daughters, Hayley, 17, and Michaela, 11.
Defense lawyers say they will also challenge the constitutionality of the death penalty and argue that the judge unfairly expelled one of the jurors, who had been critical of prosecutors, and improperly pressured a verdict by making the unusual decision to get the jury to deliberate in a weekend.
The jurors were not kidnapped.
But their arguments about the effect of intense media coverage of the trial could be the biggest source of interest.
They noted in a protest against the verdict, filed last month, that the case dominated the media scene in Connecticut and was being discussed during the election campaign by candidates for governor and the U.S. Senate.
They maintained that the computer media continued to fan the flames of emotion in the case.
“The daily stampede of tweets from the media, cameras and journalists outside the courthouse,” the lawyers wrote, “did not resemble anything that had been seen before here in New Haven, and perhaps even nationally.”
Their focus on coverage of the Twitter system is controversial.
In interviews, some journalists said the claim that instant news was more incendiary than press releases delivered more slowly was a luddist view that would impoverish the court’s policy governing media coverage of future trials.
But some lawyers said appellate courts were often drawn to arguments that social and technological changes required adaptation by the courts.
Hayes’s lawyers insist on this claim.
In their case, they made reference to the 1966 Supreme Court decision that overturned Dr. Sheppard’s conviction due to media coverage of the trial and said they would invoke the need for new rules for new media.
“This case,” they wrote, “represents Sheppard v. Maxwell’s case of the 21st century.”
Can civility bring divisions closer together?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a minimum of civility broke out in Washington this week.
Is this a harbinger of true bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the rapid return to partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and congressional leaders produced no breakthrough on the big issues that need to be addressed during the “Lame Duck” session.
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion about the differences between the two sides as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points.
Wednesday’s public meeting of the president’s deficit commission was just as civilised, despite the political differences that remain among members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created a mutual respect transcending the ideological gap; but which, however, still divides the members.
This is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
Both sides are now in a period of trial and mutual testing with a view to obtaining signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and voter patience for a renewed partisan war.
That’s why Tuesday’s meeting and subsequent comments from attendees unveiled a minimum of requirements or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid climate change that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxes, expenses, healthcare or entitlements, both parties remain miles away.
Still, the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
“There is no doubt that things have changed in tone,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now alongside the Center for Ethics and Public Policy.
“This is inevitable after the election.
Elections arouse partisan passions, and then they fade away.
That's good."
On some issues, including those on the agenda of the "Lame Duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of that.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of it, either permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on extending unemployment benefits, if only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployment benefits to unemployed workers.
After Tuesday’s meeting at the White House, more optimism hangs over a possible agreement on the issues raised during the “Lame Duck” session, with the ratification of the “New START” pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that fruitful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "lame duck" session will not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, if not inevitable.
“Once the things that need to be done are done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations,” he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civility would lead to genuine cooperation.
“I consider most of what’s going on between now and 2012 as a pre-show or shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012,” he said.
The reasons for this are closely linked to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters present at the tea that contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know they must try to live up to their promises to cut public spending and repeal the new health care law.
These partisan positions are already clear in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the Deficit Committee which include reforming the tax code and raising certain taxes, pushing back the retirement age and cutting spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and, according to themselves, imposed the deficit issue on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes on the 18-member commission to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they have struggled to reach that number.
The greatest resistance remains among the group's elected officials, suggesting that there are few grounds or willingness to compromise on tax issues, at least today.
Galston plans two phases in the fights between the White House and congressional Republicans.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, as Republicans challenge Obama over budget, taxes, and health care; followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
Public opinion.
There is ample evidence that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see both parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to a stalemate, as in 1995, then both parties will carefully observe the reaction of the public.
Whoever is judged a loss will have to change course and find compromises.
But that would be an optimistic point of view.
The partisan spirit and polarization is greater today than it was in the mid-1990s, and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and congressional Republicans than there was then between President Bill Clinton and Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a more substantial election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on the part of both sides to find common ground on the issues that still divide them.
leaked US documents describe Moscow as a haven of corruption
Control of the city is in the hands of a "Kleptocracy" and passes some of the bribes and protection money it collects to the Kremlin, the U.S. Embassy in Russia reported in a note in February.
The police and the Federal Security Service make huge rackets that help explain the high cost of living in Moscow, he said.
They collect money not only from legitimate businesses but also from organized criminal groups.
Every layer of bureaucracy – what Prime Minister Vladimir Putin called the “vertical of power” – is taking its share as money moves up the ladder.
The memo, which was sent to Washington under the name of Ambassador John Beyrle, was posted Wednesday by Wikileaks on its website.
The note is based on sources whose names have been redacted.
It was written while Yury Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow; and he is largely held responsible for corruption.
He was fired in October by President Dmitry Medvedev but there have been few clean-ups since then.
Luzhkov and his wife, Elena Batourina, who owns a leading construction company, have consistently denied corruption charges over the years; and he has won several defamation lawsuits over these charges.
In September, he told a Russian TV channel, when asked about a documentary suggesting he was corrupt: “It’s crazy, it’s to be thrown away, it’s anything.”
The Russians believe, by an overwhelming majority, that their society is corrupt; according to polls.
But it is unusual to find the information set out in an embassy report; and it is unheard of to conceive that it would be up to diplomats from a foreign country to do so.
The direct link between the Moscow city government and crime has led some to call it “dysfunctional” and claim that the government functions more like a kleptocracy than a government, according to the embassy’s note.
Criminal elements enjoy a “krysha” (a term used in the criminal/mafia world that literally means “roof” or protection) that passes through the police, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Ministry of the Interior (MVD) and the prosecutor’s office, as well as through the entire bureaucracy of the Moscow city government.
"Analysts identify a three-tiered structure in the criminal world of Moscow."
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"The FSB, the MVD and the militias are at the second level."
“Finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level.”
“This is an inefficient system in which criminal groups fill a void in certain areas where the city does not provide certain services.”
The report says that the FSB is brewing money from the biggest companies and that the police are targeting the small ones.
A source, he said, “explained that business owners in Moscow understood that it was better to get protection from the MVD and FSB (rather than organized crime groups) because, not only do they have more weapons, more means and more power than criminal groups but they are also protected by law.”
“That’s why the demand for protection by criminal gangs is no longer so high.”
The note notes that although the collection of money is extensive, the protection itself can be uneven; even those who pay are sometimes subject to arrest.
Those who do not pay quickly see their business closed under one pretext or another.
Medvedev mentioned the fight against corruption several times, but he admitted the lack of progress.
The embassy note relays reports of men bringing suitcases, probably filled with money, to the Kremlin.
“In its fight against corruption, Medvedev depends on bureaucrats,” Georgiy Satarov, director of Moscow’s think tank Indem, said in a recent interview.
“But he’s part of that bureaucracy.”
“He is not part of a political class because there are none in Russia.”
Without politics, without opposition, without separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
According to the Indem, the costs of corruption would amount to more than $300 billion per year.
The country was ranked 154th in a recent survey on the global perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (countries are ranked from at least to the most corrupt).
The disclosure of the note of the US embassy, which was only realized yesterday, late in the evening, Moscow time, will certainly stir up discontent within the Russian government; although Luzhkov may be blamed, to some extent, for Moscow’s failures, this could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to show that it is solving the problem.
Interviewed by CNN by Larry King, Putin hypothesized that the WikiLeaks documents could be a fabrication and reacted angrily to remarks that U.S. diplomats had leaked by calling him Batman and bringing Medvedev closer to Robin.
“The problem is that it’s about our interaction, which is an important factor in domestic policy in this country,” he said.
“But to be honest with you, we didn’t suspect it would be achieved with such arrogance, such pressure and, you know, in opposition to ethics.”
Khmer Rouge veterans forced to face the past
In a poorly lit classroom with decrepit, low-quality concrete walls, the headmaster of Anlong Veng High School spoke about the man who built it, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge, Ta Mok.
"Everyone here loves Ta Mok."
“He was a good leader; and he cared about his people,” said 42-year-old Sreng Kor Ma.
Known as "the butcher" for his brutality, when he was head of the Khmer Rouge, this commander remains popular in this isolated stronghold of former Khmer Rouge in northwest Cambodia where he built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure; and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live today.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge surrendered to the government, Anlong Veng’s long-standing loyalty is finally called into question.
In April, a local truth and reconciliation forum allowed victims to publicly confront people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government distributed a high school textbook that, for the first time, taught the Khmer Rouge history to the children of its former soldiers.
And in July, a Cambodian court, jointly headed by the United Nations, handed down its first sentence against a former Khmer Rouge member, sentencing the former head of the infamous Tuol Sleng torture center, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as “Duch,” to 35 years in prison.
In the face of these developments, anxiety has increased among Khmer Rouge veterans of Anlong Veng; complicating reconciliation efforts and their willingness to reintegrate into Cambodian society.
“There is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge but they are powerless to do anything,” said Chhang Youk, director of the Cambodia Documentation Center, an independent body that conducts research on the regime.
“For them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious but the regime became a symbol of evil.”
"The situation generates divisions within families."
During the Khmer Rouge rule in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, about 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and overthrew the Pol Pot-U.S. government in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army fled to Cambodia’s border with Thailand.
There, they launched an insurgency that lasted until the last of the movements surrendered in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary led the guerrillas from their base in the mountains of western Cambodia and the jungle, Ta Mok was preparing a sequel to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990s, after a UN-sponsored peace deal led to the country's first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of Khmer Rouge fighters began defecting to the government, culminating with the capitulations of Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Khieu Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had stood up, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in a Phnom Penh prison in 2006 pending trial.
Without their benefactors, most Khmer Rouge veterans have sunk into poverty, common in rural Cambodia; and many remain nostalgic for the movement.
Although a few elite Khmer Rouge officers have kept their positions as local leaders in exchange for laying down their arms, they are unskilled farmers with low rank and record.
“These people received very little follow-up after the capitulation,” said Sok Leang of the Center for Justice and Reconciliation, which organizes public forums throughout Cambodia, including in Anlong Veng.
“They are soaked in the regime’s agrarian utopian ideology.”
“They were raised in a setting where doing business is a foreign concept.”
Sor Lim, 55, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before settling in 1998 as a poor rice farmer.
“Life under the Khmer Rouge was good,” he said.
"Your Mok feeds everyone."
But now life is difficult because we have to provide for ourselves.”
The ongoing Khmer Rouge court has also caused concern here.
The court is expected to begin sentencing Nuon Chea, Khieu Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge minister, early next year.
The court's mandate is to try senior leaders and those most responsible for the crimes, but it did not say whether it would prosecute beyond these four cases.
It would take more to calm the fears in Anlong Veng.
The latest media speculation has turned to 64-year-old Im Chaem, a former district chief in Banteay Meanchey province during Khmer Rouge rule in the 1970s.
In 2007, she told researchers at the Cambodia Documentation Centre that she had overseen the construction of the Trapeang Thma dam, a project where thousands of forced laborers are believed to have died.
Recently, on a scorching evening, Im Chaem was returning from work at the field near his wooden house on stilts, on a dirt road outside of Anlong Veng.
As the sun cast long shadows over the parched grass, Im Chaem refused to discuss his past among the Khmer Rouge.
If the court summoned her, she said, she would refuse to go.
“Cambodia is at peace and stable,” she said.
“If there are more prosecutions, there will be war.”
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who defected from the Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that instability would occur if the court prosecuted multiple suspects; although experts and historians dispute this.
“Cambodia needs to dig a hole and bury the past,” he said.
But facing the past is all Cambodia needs to do to move forward, says Youk Chhang, of the documentation center.
“Reconciliation in Khmer terms is about reconnecting broken pieces,” he says.
“We need to put these pieces together so we can understand.”
The center produced the first government-approved manual on the Khmer Rouge, “A History of Democratic Kampuchea, Composed of 75 Pages.”
He distributed it to Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the Ministry of Education’s history textbooks, designed for high schools, which contained less than four pages about the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia, the youth of Anlong Veng know only a few details about the Khmer Rouge, despite the city’s ties to the regime.
Touch Valeak, 19, a student at Anlong Veng High School, said the new textbook helps students understand an important part of their history.
But his parents reacted with skepticism when he came home with the book to study.
“My family rejects many parts of the manual and the court,” he says.
“They are wary because they don’t know exactly how many people the court will prosecute.”
Such resistance has made the reconciliation process complex and difficult, Leang said.
But public forums, the manual and the court are starting to make an impact, he said.
However, the Khmer Rouge still have a powerful attraction here.
In the heights of the Dangrek mountains, a path, invaded by weeds and dotted with plastic bags, leads to a rectangle of black soot, covered with a rusty sheet metal roof.
Pol Pot’s body was burned here on a pile of tires after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, 31, a roadside mobile phone saleswoman, said she didn’t know much about the man who was cremated there.
"But he has a great spirit; and many people go there to pray," she said.
It was Nuom Sothea’s birthday and later that day she planned to walk to Pol Pot’s final resting place where she would leave a bunch of ripe bananas in hopes of bringing luck.
Belarus agrees to give up its stockpile of military-grade uranium
The government of Belarus announced Wednesday that it will abandon its stockpile of highly enriched uranium, an essential component for nuclear weapons; this decision is part of a surprise victory of President Obama’s campaign to secure nuclear materials worldwide.
The deal was leaked in a joint statement issued after Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton met here with Belarusian Foreign Minister Sergei Martynov on the sidelines of a security summit.
The US government had been trying for years to convince Belarus to give up highly enriched uranium and seemed to have cleared the horizon last spring.
But U.S. officials told the Washington Post that some classified operations were carried out with Belarus in the past two months to remove 187 pounds of military-grade uranium from a Belarus research center.
