Red Bull triumphs in F1 with secret Siemens weapon
Software creates improvements on cars in real time.
As soon as Red Bull entered the world of Formula 1 in 2004, its history in this select world of speed was marked by surprise and success.
At first, no one took into account the options of a new team that had just arrived, despite the upward trajectory of the last few seasons, past November, in the last phase of the championship they all bet on the triumph of Ferrari Fernando Alonso.
Without lowering the champion's ability as a driver, the German Sebastien Vette, nor the capacity of the Renault engine that propels his car, in the world of Formula 1 we speak of the legend of the "secret weapon" that the multinational company Siemens has put in the hands of Red Bull to transform it into a winning team.
It is in fact a powerful process simulation software that the German company launched on the market in 2007 with objectives far removed from high motoring competition.
Named PLM, this powerful computer instrument has been used to create assembly lines from manufacturers factories all over the world, power stations, high-precision instruments.
The objective is to reproduce, accurately simulate the product or process before building it in a real way, avoiding avoidable defects and costs.
PLM has facilitated the development of Canon cameras, Sukhoi aircraft or Nissan’s most famous commercial vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of Siemens’ industrial division, explains the fact that the use of this computer instrument in its Formula 1 plant allowed Red Bull to create and execute “in a few hours, almost in real time”, the modifications, changes and improvements detected during races and trials.
Russwurm explains that the 1992 teams had an average of 10 technicians on their teams who were able to introduce a maximum of three or four vehicle upgrades each season.
In the Red Bull team today 180 young professionals of high qualification work who, equipped with powerful computer equipment analyze and project all kinds of modifications on the cars.
The head of Siemens explained that the PLM software is able to analyze and improve all the elements of the Red Bull cars except the engine, which is the exclusive responsibility of Renault.
The materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are modified.
Changes can shift from simulator virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced laser production systems and high-tech autoclaves.
As the only limitation of this insanity of technological development there is the amount of $40 million that each Formula 1 team can spend as a limit each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has set up the high-tech plant to create and produce its cars in a locality 50 kilometres from London.
These are two buildings where visits, especially for journalists, are restricted.
Everything that happens there is considered "top secret".
The staff for this assignment is 580 people, including two pilots, the champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
The Red Bull Formula 1 hero, no doubt, is the recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
Among the immense technological resources that the brand of energy drinks has put at the service of its participation in the circuits, there are other hidden protagonists, whose activity is invaluable and the notoriety zero.
The plant’s chief technology officer, Steve Nevey, says that five years ago it could be said that R&D progress in the case of race cars brought 50% of the victories and the drivers were responsible for the rest.
Today these percentages have changed and technology accounts for 85% of the success, while drivers bring 15% of the added value.
Nevey admits that the Vettels or Webbers will never be replaced by computers, because "they are unpredictable gladiators".
