Zapatero and the German Red Line
Berlin opted to stay in the euro, but it set the conditions for the whole Union.
Market tensions have provoked a government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Rodriguez Zapatero has announced new methods of adjustment, which vary from tax reductions for SMEs, regulation of private investment agencies or abolition of the 426 euros of assistance to the unemployed without professional contribution to the privatization of 49% of AENA, the management of the airports of Barajas and El Prat and 30% of the Lotteries of the State.
On the other hand, Vice President Elena Salgado, with the support of former President Felipe Gonzalez, joins Chancellor Angela Merkel’s criticisms of her responsibility to detach the current crisis.
How should these movements be interpreted?
It should be mentioned that Merkel’s position is not a mistake in her communicative policy.
On the contrary, it is another restriction of the difficult process of redefining the euro.
And there Germany has a radically new vision of what its future should be, which shocks with that of maintaining the old traditions of most of its partners.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate on the three possible exits from the crisis.
The first, a strong euro, integrated by itself, Austria and Holland, among other countries, and the south would abandon the monetary zone.
The second, the recovery of the Mark, even if now it sounds like science fiction, with a very favorable current of opinion, nearly a 50% of the population.
The third, a new conception of the euro, in line with the German proposals for greater macroeconomic control, budgetary rigor, fines to countries that transgress them, possible suspensions of payments from one of them and extension to the private sector of the costs of potential adjustments.
The German position is clear and has been defined for a long time, so now there is no room for excuses.
First, in 2009, when both the IMF and the European Commission were boosting deficits, the German government invented a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of divergence between what Germany thought we had to do (tax austerity plans and stability of public finances) and what its European partners, including France, practiced.
The second blow from the central European country was when Merkel hardly prolonged the decision to save Greece.
From that moment it was the subject of fierce criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and the public opinion and published it were against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, towards the end of October, Merkel again expresses a clear position, calling for the reform of the Union treaties to make possible the rescue of a country and at the same time force private lenders to bear a share of the cost.
This position has been interpreted as anti-European, as it precipitated the Irish crisis and the rest.
But his proposal, although a little watered down, was approved and, in the following months, we should attend the reform process of the Union that makes these measures possible from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it doesn’t think it will cross.
And it tells us all that, even if we now have to take measures with which we may not agree too much, from that date on, the old functioning of the euro would have ended.
2013 will mean the birth of a new monetary zone, in which countries that break the rules will be severely punished, they may be forced to declare themselves in default of payments and, in this case, the private sector will also bear a share of the costs.
Germany warns us that we must follow a severe growth path with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness and positive external balances.
An alternative based on debt and construction, with huge gaps in the balance of payments, like the one that presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, will simply not be tolerated.
The bet is clear.
And it would be wrong not to hear it.
It is not just a question of reducing the public deficit to 3% in 2013.
What we are asked to do is much harder.
And what he absolutely must not do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will bring greater tranquility to us.
And let us seize the opportunity we have been given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also heard it in this form and his double statement (the reforms promised after Saturday’s meeting with the big companies and yesterday’s announcement of the new measures) suggests that, despite Merkel’s criticism, the path has been opened to the thesis that it is necessary to put the house in order.
But the red line that Germany has drawn is there, and they don't seem to be moving it.
And among the possibilities we are considering, we cannot exclude the possibility of abandoning a monetary zone too full of countries that are not very serious.
And in that case, Germany will always be able to tell us that she had warned us.
Sport and fraud of the law
The tricks similar to those of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not the desire to escape punishment.
The expulsion in principle by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) during the match of November 23 against Ajax in the Champions League has made a lot of ink about the anti-sports character of such behavior and whether both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As we know, a few minutes before finishing the match (which their team already clearly won), both players deliberately lost time when they made mistakes to determine the referee to show them the second yellow card.
Thus, and since Real Madrid will eventually be leader of his group, the two players will fulfill the regulatory sanction during the next match of the play-off against Auxerre and will be able to move without cards to the next phase.
In the end, the UEFA Disciplinary Committee sanctioned the team's coach Jose Mourinho with two matches and various economic sums to the players involved.
The provocation of a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, if not rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, unwritten but followed rules, of this sport.
Part of the debate that emerged in the case related is due to the fact that this had as protagonist a team from the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem displays nobility and honor and which in past occasions has fined its players for similar acts) and to the dramatization orchestrated, it seems, by Mourinho, which adds one more episode to his dilated and provocative history of his technician histrionic.
In any case, the debate asks whether this type of conduct not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is to say, whether with these actions one commits a fraud of law; because, in fact, they are respectful actions with the sports regulation, but seem to elude its meaning.
The question is to consider the type of harm they cause to sportsmanship.
One of the assets that includes sportsmanship is the physical integrity of opposing players, an aspect that with these actions has not been endangered, that is, there has been no violent play.
Another of these assets that are alluded to with the correct game is to prevent the undercover players team from unfairly taking advantage of the opposite team, which is not the case either.
However, the paradoxical fact of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it does not accommodate what is normally characterized as cheating or fraud of the law, because its violation of the rules was not carried out in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but their action precisely tried to be as obvious as possible to receive the penalty of the referee.
They waited and they gladly accepted the sanction.
Another issue is the type of benefit that offenders receive from the intentional misconduct examined.
Here it seems necessary to note that one does not put in a position of disadvantage to the rival and one does not get an advantage in the same match either, because obviously the result of the action supposes the fact of leaving their own team with fewer players.
And that’s not a useful strategy for the next game either, as the club could not count on these players.
Obviously the advantage is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But this is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, because the team could be eliminated suddenly and apart from that, with this action the players complete a penalty match and move on to the second round of cards, in which the suspension due to the accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first round.
So, climbing the ladder is not so clear that it is an advantage.
Ultimately, these actions are not contrary to sportsmanship, which is still part of strategic decisions that promote the maximum profit of what the rules allow.
In our case, the players did not act to avoid the application of the sanction (this would indeed be a clear case of fraud of the law), otherwise they chose rather the moment in which they submitted to it.
They made a strategic decision without avoiding the penalty or running away from it.
Even if the boundary between genius and fraud of the law is diffuse, on this occasion I think we have had a clear case of genius.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises because of two factors: because there have been two self-expulsions and because of the way of transmitting the director to provoke them.
The harm caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as much ethical as aesthetic.
