However, this is not a traditional arrest order.
This one is not new, otherwise it dates from November 20th.
And this one has nothing to do with the latest filtration of more than a quarter million diplomatic documents of the United States but with the accusations of sexual abuse that the Australian faces in Sweden.
In addition, Wikileaks’ founding lawyer Mark Stephens says that “the police know where and how to contact Mr. Assange.”
On the 20th the international police force with headquarters in Lyon (France) dictated the order at the request of Sweden, but it did not make it public until yesterday, after having received the authorization of the authorities of that country.
Thus, all 188 Interpol countries were told to identify or locate Assange “to obtain his provisional arrest and extradition.”
Even though Interpol cannot give the order for the arrest of an individual affected by a red alert, many of the member countries, according to the organization's explanations, consider the red notice a free route for arrest -- which the national police force must carry out -- especially if they have a bilateral extradition agreement, as is the case in Sweden and England, where Assange is believed to be.
The move outraged Assange’s lawyers, who yesterday published a letter denouncing the fact that the 39-year-old WikiLeaks founder was willing to answer questions from Swedish authorities via video conferencing.
They also recall that Assange solicited and obtained the permit to leave Sweden from the prosecutor of his case, which is compared to the famous Lavrentiy Pavlovich Beria, head of the security of Stalin.
“It seems to be a hunt, not a legal persecution,” the letter said.
While the world is looking for him – and in Australia his mother is defending his son’s innocence – Assange continues to be in an unknown place, but he is not silent.
On Monday he gave an undetermined interview to the editor of Time magazine through Skype, a conversation in which he demanded the resignation of U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton.
