The European Union changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Individuals must go to the Visa Applicant Service Centers prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be reduced.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing procedure at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to report to the Visa Applicant Service Centers (VACs) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have some advantages for aspirants, among which the following are mentioned:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to get an appointment, another payment for processing the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The aspirant will make a one-time payment that will cover all three services.
The current fee will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 in the case of visas with application (this includes visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
Persons wishing to renew their visa will not be required to present themselves for an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only present themselves at the nearest CSA where they will present the documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be taken in the CSA, applicants who want a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will stay there for less time than before.
Likewise, visa applicants at the Consulates of Ciudad Juarez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For more information on the new visa application process, visit http://mexico.usembussy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
