Dupont partially blamed
Quebec City radio host Stéphane Dupont suffered a partial setback in front of the Canadian Broadcast Standards Council (CBSC) for controversial comments about social assistance and Haitians as well as his crude language on the air.
The CBSC found that Mr. Dupont and his CHOI 98.1 FM team had the right to express their opinions, but that some comments contained "inaccurate information about social assistance, unduly negative representations of Haitians and coarse language that is not appropriate for programs broadcast during the day."
The Commission also found that a discussion of suicide, including the release of the names of two persons who committed suicide, did not violate the broadcasting codes.
The CBSC had received several complaints about comments made during broadcasts between 2008 and 2010.
The first decision was made following a complaint by the Front commun des personnes assistés sociales du Québec.
The group complained that the amounts cited in the issue were inaccurate.
Facilitators must present strong rather than misleading information.
Regarding suicide, the animator Stéphane Dupont had felt that suicide is a cowardly gesture.
The majority of Committee members concluded that the message was that suicide should not be seen as a solution to life's problems.
"The majority of the Committee considers that the episodes in question of 'Dupont le midi' addressed a sensitive subject in a fair and appropriate manner."
No blame has been laid on him.
The last dispute concerned statements that followed the earthquake in Haiti.
Stéphane Dupont and Jean-René Dufort had then engaged in a media face-to-face that had generated a lot of reactions.
The CHOI host said he had not made any donations to help Haitians because it was not clear that the needy people would really receive the money.
The Panel believes that these comments were not abusive, but that their cumulative effect constitutes an unduly negative representation of Haitians.
"I've already served my three-day suspension on this."
“My file has been blank for a year and a half,” the host said.
In all decisions, the Committee denounces the dissemination of coarse language.
In each case, the broadcaster CHOI-FM collaborated "beyond its obligation".
The consequences are minimal for the station, which will have to, among other things, announce these decisions once during peak viewing hours within three days.
The King of Kung Fu in Montreal
The Algerian-born Montrealer Nacereddine Zemmal has an extremely special background.
