"Then the winners of each category face each other to crown a single champion, the king of kung fu."
450 million in contracts without tenders
Hydro-Québec has awarded $450 million in contracts to engineering firms for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert hydroelectric project.
At the heart of this avalanche of more than 100 contracts, a consortium composed of the firms BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor obtained the largest, that of the management of the project, for a sum of $ 295 million without tendering.
This consortium called Energy Stewardship was formed in 2004 at the same time as Hydro-Québec chose to entrust the private sector with its responsibility for managing this important $5 billion hydroelectric project.
In early 2005, the Energy Stewardship consortium closed the lucrative contract without a public call for tenders.
For the Parti Québécois, the use of consortia of companies poses a serious ethical problem that risks eliminating competition and causing prices to rise.
“This is the new way to collude and knock down competition.”
"That is to say that people, instead of doing this in a secret way, now do it in an open way," PQ MP Sylvain Simard said yesterday at a press conference.
Earlier in the morning, Mr. Simard raised the issue in the National Assembly because he said it was difficult to see how the public interest could be served in this way.
The Minister of Natural Resources, Nathalie Normandeau, responded in the afternoon, strongly denying that there was collusion for this contract.
“I’m starting to have my trip,” she said, arguing that the PQ had been “dishonest” and had “lacked rigor.”
She said that "it would be the least thing" that the PQ apologized.
The formula of consortia is a common practice all over the world.
It is usually a time-limited alliance that allows two or more companies to pool their respective expertise in order to respond to a tender for a complex project.
The Eastmain project has a high level of complexity given the scale of the work.
The project is ongoing and is scheduled to run until 2012.
However, the contract was awarded without competition acting; there was negotiation.
Also, the consortium formula is no longer an exception in Quebec, even for relatively simple projects.
As Le Devoir revealed last week, the formula of consortia in the consulting engineering sector is being investigated by the government.
A quick overview of Quebec’s business register makes it possible to count more than 200 consortia, some of which seem permanent.
Thus, Dessau works in partnership with most of its main competitors, including CIMA+, Génivar, SNC-Lavalin and others Roche and Tecsult.
Each combination, and there are dozens of them, brings us back to one and the same legal person, Dessau.
With regard to the Energy Stewardship consortium, Minister Normandeau pointed out that "the James Bay territory responds to particular workforce dynamics and that Hydro-Québec has been responding to them in a particular way since the 1970s".
Eastmain project's big boss, Réal Laporte of the James Bay Energy Corporation (JBEC), gave an explanation that raised eyebrows over the fact that the project's management contract was awarded over-the-counter.
"If you go to tender and there are few bidders, your prices will be higher."
"You have two choices: either you take the people who are in that market and you say: we will negotiate a satisfactory deal and with a good price."
“But the idea is that it’s not the price that matters, it’s the competence of the people,” Laporte said.
This contract awarded to the Energy Stewardship consortium is part of a long list of contracts of more than $50,000 obtained by the Parti Québécois.
The contracts were awarded by Hydro-Québec or SEBJ for the Eastmain-1-A-Sarcelle-Rupert project.
After verification, Le Devoir counted 109 consulting engineering contracts awarded between 2002 and March 2010 to firms or their subsidiaries, including soil laboratories.
SNC-Lavalin won 22 contracts, Genivar won 16, Tecsult 14 and Dessau 10, not to mention its participation in Énergie gérance.
All contracts have been negotiated.
They total $449,783,344, including the Energy Stewardship contract of $295,131,564.
Sylvain Simard has suggested that the four firms that make up the consortium (BPR, Dessau, Groupe SM and Axor) are "well known to the Quebec Liberal Party".
Minister Normandeau has dropped that the PQ is also linked to these firms that "finance" it, before specifying that it was rather its leaders.
Responsible consumption barometer - The "green" label does not inspire confidence
Greener, but frankly skeptical.
Quebec consumers have very little confidence in sustainable development players, but also in fair brands and green certifications to guide their choices.
Worse, even if he is immersed in a media universe where messages in favor of a more responsible consumption abound, he deplores a lack of credible information, a deficiency that he even describes as a brake on his commitment, says the Barometer of responsible consumption, whose first reading was delivered yesterday.
Even if they increased the consumption of so-called socially responsible products in 2010, Quebecers seem to give very little credit to those who try to sell them.
Two thirds of them say they do not believe the companies' environmental commitment as well as the companies' green advertising, reveals the measurement tool developed by the Observatoire de la consommation responsable de l'Université Sherbrooke.
Another observation: half of consumers doubt the reliability of official certifications affixed to so-called fair trade products, but also the credibility of products and brands displaying themselves as being eco-responsible, says the Barometer.
In the same vein, the discourse of politicians on this topic is taken seriously by only 14.6% of Quebecers.
However, information on responsible consumption seems essential to stimulate this part of consumption currently animated by nearly a third of Quebec consumers.
Indeed, the emptiness and questionable nature of the information would calm the ardour of 46% of consumers.
This is the second brake identified by the Barometer, after the higher price of these products.
In addition, a third of Quebecers are also suspicious of the alleged performance of green products or services that they are trying to put in their hands.
On another note, consumers were almost half in 2010 to have changed their habit and especially changed the brand of one or more products to meet their conviction.
At 61%, they also favored purchases from merchants in their neighborhood and preferred the purchase of food products grown in their region, says the Barometer.
Greener and more responsible - the responsible consumption index has reached 64 out of a maximum of 100 for this year - the Homo consumus of Quebec likes to present itself as the king of recycling who seeks to reduce its environmental footprint by worrying about the protection of animals.
But his social and ecological awareness seems to remain outside his car, says the Barometer: in 2010, barely 28% of Quebecers reported using public transit or advocated carpooling to defend their green interests.
Walking and cycling were also supported by 39.1% of the participants in this large behavioral survey, which has just taken its first shot.
