The unemployment rate remained stable in France in the third quarter
The unemployment rate in France according to the International Labour Office (ILO) remained stable at 9.3% in mainland France (9.7% including the overseas departments), show the seasonally adjusted data (CVS) provisional published Thursday by INSEE.
The number of unemployed stands at 2,631 million in metropolitan France.
Data for the second quarter were confirmed at 9.3% of the working population in metropolitan France and 9.7% with the DOMs.
Over the course of a year, the unemployment rate increased by 0.1 percentage point.
More broadly, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France did not work in the third quarter but wanted to work, whether or not they were available within two weeks to work and whether or not they were looking for a job.
The situation of young people on the labour market has deteriorated further, with a further increase in the unemployment rate, to 24.2% in metropolitan France (+ 0.9 points over three months, + 0.5 points over one year) and 25% including the French overseas departments.
In the third quarter, 637,000 young people aged 15 to 24 were unemployed within the meaning of the ILO.
Seniors, for their part, experienced a slight increase in unemployment, to 6.4% in metropolitan France (+0.2 points over three months as well as over one year), or 482,000 people aged 50 or over, and 6.6% with the French overseas departments.
Only 25-49 year-olds benefited from stable unemployment in the third quarter, at 8.3% in mainland France (-0.1 point over three months, +0.1 point over one year) and 8.8% throughout France.
INSEE has not published monthly unemployment rates since 2006, after a controversy over its calculation method.
Eurostat, the statistical agency of the European Union, continues to do so and announced on Tuesday a rate of 9.8% for France (DOM included) in October after 9.9% in September.
