Clotilde Reiss affair: the Elysée exaggerated the mediation of Syria
For more than ten months, from July 2009 to May 2010, the fate of Clotilde Reiss, the young French researcher arrested in Iran for "espionage", held the opinion in suspense in France, put diplomacy on alert, and accentuated the deterioration of relations between Paris and Tehran.
All under the watchful eye of U.S. diplomats.
The American documents obtained by WikiLeaks and consulted by Le Monde reveal some of the undersides of this crisis.
They describe how the Elysee explained its strategy to the Americans, going so far as to give them advice for dealing with their own “hostage” crises in Iran (a small group of hikers).
They show how French officials sought to convince Washington that the release of the young Frenchwoman had not been matched by the release of Majid Kakavand, an Iranian detained in France and wanted by the American justice for trafficking materials for the benefit of the Iranian nuclear program.
Finally, they cast a harsh light on how the French presidency sought to manipulate the media to accredit the idea that Syrian President Bashar al-Assad had played a central role in the liberation of Clotilde Reiss.
In fact, it was not.
A diplomatic cable written on August 12, 2009 in Paris is titled "Iran: French comments on how to handle hostage cases".
The Elysée’s advisor for strategic affairs, François Richier, accompanied by the director of the Quai d’Orsay for North Africa and the Middle East, Patrice Paoli, meet with the American diplomat Kathleen Allegrone.
They explain the French method to him.
They advise Americans to do the same to repatriate their own forcibly detained nationals to Iran.
"Make noise," they say, "always hammer" in the media the words "fundamental human rights," "innocence," "immediate liberation."
It is necessary in order to embarrass the Iranian regime, sensitive to its image.
“Do it all the more because the Iranians are asking you not to do it.”
Because, past the attempts of discussions through discreet channels, "silence will not solve anything", the Iranians are "masters in dilatory maneuvers".
Mr Richier added that the arrest of foreigners is "a familiar Iranian tactic: hostage-taking for political blackmail".
He announces that the release from prison of Clotilde Reiss (which will take place on August 16, the day she takes refuge in the embassy of France) "will require the payment of a large sum of money" (230,000 euros deposit).
And he says the Elysée anticipates other hostage crises, a phenomenon that "will get worse".
The Iranians could “in the near future arrest another of the approximately 1,800 French citizens living in Iran,” he said.
28 August 2009.
Clotilde Reiss has been released from prison for 12 days, but remains stranded in Iran.
An information is disseminated: the Iranian Majid Kakavand, whose extradition is requested by the United States for an illegal traffic of sensitive electronic equipment to Iran, is released in Paris, on the decision of a judge.
The U.S. Embassy, like many observers, is questioning this troubling coincidence.
For Washington, which is tracking Iran’s clandestine networks for acquiring material for the nuclear program, the expansion of Majid Khakavand is bad news.
Did France accept a bargain?
The liberation of the Iranian against that of the French?
During a new interview with Kathleen Allegrone on September 4, François Richier assures that this is not the case.
The Elysee, he said, not only “was completely taken by surprise by the judge’s decision,” but sought to oppose it.
"There were lively exchanges between the French presidency and the guard of the seals" (at the time, Michèle Alliot-Marie), but "the French government cannot reverse the judicial decision," he observes.
Mr. Richier also wants to demonstrate that Majid Kakavand remains under the "close" surveillance of the French intelligence services.
The Elysée adviser dials a phone number, hangs up, then informs the American diplomat that the Iranian "is currently located in buildings in Paris managed by the Iranian embassy".
During the detention of Clotilde Reiss in Iran, the Elysée is sparing its efforts, through communiqués and "leaks" organized in the media, to make believe that Syrian President Bashar Al-Assad plays an "important" and "influential" role as "mediator".
The Americans observe this activity not without irony, and find that the manipulation bears fruit since several press articles reflect the official French version.
A telegram dated August 25, 2009 evokes "the media 'blitz' of French officials".
On what basis is so much "gratitude" expressed towards Mr. Assad, wonders the embassy in Paris.
Despite their laudatory statements, French officials privately acknowledge that they have only a vague notion of what the Syrians actually did.
The document then looks at the reasons why the Elysee has poured into this fiction.
The intense communication effort “aimed at validating Sarkozy’s policy of opening up to Syria,” he said.
