Vengeance Hackers and Diligence Spies
The WikiLeaks case has a double value.
On the one hand, it is an apparent scandal, a scandal that only appears as a scandal in the face of the hypocrisy that governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other hand, it heralds profound changes at the international level, and foreshadows a future dominated by regression.
But let's proceed in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks is the confirmation of the fact that each file constituted by a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about Berlusconi's sexual habits only report what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those owned by Berlusconi), and Gaddafi's ominously cartoonish profile has long been for cabaret artists.
The rule that secret files should only be composed of previously known news is essential to the dynamics of the secret service, and not only in this century.
If you go to a bookstore devoted to esoteric publications, you will see that each book repeats (on the Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, the Templars or the Rose-Croix) exactly what was already written in previous books.
And this is not only because the author of occult texts does not like to do unpublished research (or does not know where to look for news on the non-existent), but because those who devote themselves to occultism believe only what they already know, and who reconfirm what they had already learned.
This is the mechanism of Dan Brown's success.
I'm going for the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or of limited mind) the head of the secret services (otherwise he could be, what do I know, editor at Libération), who retains as true only what he recognizes.
The top secret Berlusconi information that the U.S. Embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same information that Newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every educated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the heads of state can call each other or take a plane to meet at dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises of representation, have turned into centers of espionage.
Any viewer of investigative films knows this very well, and it is only through hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put U.S. diplomacy in the wrong light.
Second, the idea that any hacker could capture the most secret secrets of the most powerful country in the world is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
So the scandal does not put the victims so much in crisis as the “harbours”.
But let’s get to the deep nature of what happened.
Once upon a time, in Orwell's time, one could conceive of all power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been completely fulfilled since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway taken, and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when we demonstrate, as it happens now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker – elected as the citizen’s avenger – can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a real secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that knowing everything about Berlusconi’s or Merkel’s character is indeed an empty secret, because it is in the public domain; but revealing, as WikiLeaks did, that Hillary Clinton’s secrets were empty secrets means taking away all power from her.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but has done too much to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this wound inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to post any reserved information online - that would be like publishing it on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it is just as obvious that with current technologies, it is futile to hope to be able to maintain confidential reports by phone.
There is nothing easier than finding out if and when a head of state flew in and contacted one of his colleagues.
How can private and reserved relationships be maintained in the future?
I know that, for the moment, my forecast is science fiction and is therefore romantic, but I am forced to imagine government agents who move discreetly in stagecoaches with uncontrollable routes, being carriers only of messages learned by heart or, at the most, hiding the rare information written in the heel of a shoe.
The information will be kept in a single copy in locked drawers: basically, the Watergate spying attempt was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that technology is now advancing in crab, that is, backwards.
A century after the wireless telegraph revolutionized communications, the Internet has reestablished a wire telegraph (telephone).
The videocassettes (analog) had allowed film researchers to explore a film step by step, going forward and backward and discovering all the secrets of the editing, while now the CDs (digital) only allow to jump from chapter to chapter, that is to say by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, you get from Rome to Milan in three hours, while by plane, and the trips it includes, it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that the politics and the techniques of communication turn to horse-drawn cars.
One last observation.
In the past, the press tried to understand what was going on in the secret of embassies.
Now it is the embassies that are asking the press for confidential information.
Climate: how France is making promises of funding
One year after the Copenhagen Accord, it’s time to look at how fast-start or early-stage funding promises made by developed countries are being met.
And the big French hacks are revealed.
In the Copenhagen Accord, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised 7.2 billion euros over three years and France 1.26 billion euros (or 420 million a year).
At the opening of COP16, the EU released the big game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast start funding: report detailing the action of its member states, press conference, big side event, distribution of brochures...
Transparency is appreciated and appreciated: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU announced that it had provided 2.2 billion euros in 2010, putting it on track to meet its commitment of 7.2 billion euros in 2012.
But when you look at the details, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen agreement, "new and additional", in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of Official Development Assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission has considered 2009 as a reference year: international funding is maintained, and it adds $150 million over three years for fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or level of official development assistance.
In contrast, France considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 are "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to spending in previous years or to the overall level of Official Development Assistance.
In concrete terms, the total amount of France’s support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to “new and additional” financing...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses his mode of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that a loan is equivalent to a given loan.
Obviously, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to emission mitigation that rely on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present a euro that we will recover as equivalent to one euro that we give ... At the most, should only be counted as part of its commitments the cost of the loan for the lending country (equivalent to an interest rate).
But France has nothing to do with such reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% of loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros) - see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only EU country to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (in others) meet their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union spends 1 euro to meet its commitment, France spends only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice sleight of hand!
In summary, in its fast start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of the action over time and on the other hand on the reality of the financial effort.
By spending only 36.1 million euros, it manages to make believe that it spends 420 million "new and additional" consistent with its promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that it is Bercy who carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why the other Member States would continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not completely fooled...
The early finance chapter is only a small, relatively short-term issue compared to the overall climate discussion.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Hopefully this will not be the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn from this first year of early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its accounting method for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could push forward discussions on long-term financing issues (another crucial chapter currently being discussed): the question of "additionality" or how to account for loans will not be overlooked.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope is therefore that the new Minister of the Environment, Ms Kosciusko-Morizet, will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France’s fast start and its vision of “additionality” and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence necessary to move forward in the discussions.
